Assisted Voluntary Return and Reintegration (AVRR) is an indispensable part of a comprehensive approach to migration management aiming at orderly and humane return and reintegration of migrants who are unable or unwilling to remain in host countries and wish to return voluntarily to their countries of origin.

The successful implementation of AVRR programmes requires the cooperation and participation of a broad range of actors, including the migrants, civil society and the governments in both host countries and countries of origin. The partnerships created by IOM and a diverse range of national and international stakeholders are essential to the effective implementation of AVRRs - from the pre-return to the reintegration stages.

Beneficiaries


For migrants who need to return home but lack the means to do so, IOM’s AVRR programmes are often the only solution to their immediate plight. Beneficiaries of IOM’s assistance include:
· Individuals whose application for asylum was rejected or withdrawn
·  Stranded migrants
·  Victims of trafficking, and
·  Other vulnerable groups, including unaccompanied migrant children, or those with health-related needs

Vision


As a core activity of IOM, AVRR activities provide vital assistance to thousands of migrants every year. Building on experience and a world-wide network of offices and partners, IOM’s AVRR programmes promote international dialogue and cooperation on migration management issues among host and transit countries and countries of origin.

Objectives


IOM strives to support sustainable reintegration of migrants returning to a variety of contexts, recognizing, that the factors affecting the reintegration process and subsequently its sustainability are not dissimilar from those that resulted in the decision to migrate in the first place. IOM therefore asserts that reintegration can be considered sustainable when returnees have reached levels of economic self-sufficiency, social stability within their communities, and psychosocial well-being that allow them to cope with (re)migration drivers. Having achieved sustainable reintegration, returnees are able to make further migration decisions a matter of choice, rather than necessity. To achieve this objective, it is necessary to approach migrant reintegration in a comprehensive manner, considering the factors that can affect reintegration and addressing them in a way to respond to the needs of the individual returnees as well as the communities to which they return in a mutually beneficial way, and address the structural factors at play. Assistance to migrants, communities of return, and structural environments in countries of origin is therefore an essential element to ensuring sustainability of reintegration.

If you are eligible for in-kind reintegration assistance, you will receive a letter (Terms of Reference) before departure with the exact amount. With that letter, contact IOM in your country of origin within three months after arrival to start to enrol your desired activity. IOM will guide you through the process and monitor your progress until more or less one year after you have returned

Established in 1951, IOM is the leading inter-governmental organization in the field of migration and works closely with governmental, intergovernmental and non-governmental partners.

With 166 member states, a further 8 states holding observer status and offices in over 100 countries, IOM is dedicated to promoting humane and orderly migration for the benefit of all. It does so by providing services and advice to governments and migrants.

IOM works to help ensure the orderly and humane management of migration, to promote international cooperation on migration issues, to assist in the search for practical solutions to migration problems and to provide humanitarian assistance to migrants in need, including refugees and internally displaced people.

The IOM Constitution recognizes the link between migration and economic, social and cultural development, as well as to the right of freedom of movement.

IOM works in the four broad areas of migration management:

  • Migration and development
  • Facilitating migration
  • Regulating migration
  • Forced migration

IOM activities that cut across these areas include the promotion of international migration law, policy debate and guidance, protection of migrants' rights, migration health and the gender dimension of migration.

MigApp User Agreement


Please read the Privacy Policy and General Terms and Conditions governing the MigApp mobile application ("the application"). By clicking "I Agree" below, you are entering into a legally binding agreement with IOM.

Privacy Policy

1. Personal data

When you register with MigApp, you accept to provide some personal information. This includes your email address (or Skype username, Facebook username, etc.), first and last names (or alias), sex, Date of Birth, place of birth and phone number. You may also add a photograph to your profile if you wish.

You certify that all information you provide through MigApp, is true, accurate, and up-to-date. You agree to maintain the security of your account, including by using a secure password and not sharing your password.

2. Additional Information for In-App Features

Your agreement to additional terms may also be requested before accessing certain features of the application.

3. Purpose for Collecting and Processing Your Data

IOM may use your personal data (such as age, sex, country of origin, country of destination) only for the purposes of:

  ●   Contributing to migrants’ safe migration by establishing a communication channel between migrants and IOM and providing migrants with the relevant information specific to their migration experience
  ●   Helping IOM to analyse global, regional or local migration patterns and proactively respond to emerging issues, and
  ●   Improving the application’s usefulness towards achieving these Purposes.This may involve using your personal data to generate statistics and examine trends

IOM will not sell, distribute or rent personal information collected through MigApp.

4. Additional Purposes

IOM may also use and reproduce your location based data for future use in its work, provided that the datais anonymized (used in a manner that no one will be able to connect it to your identity). IOM’s additional purposes may include, but are not limited to:

  ●   Increasing knowledge and understanding of migration issues
  ●   Raising awareness in campaigns, promotional activities, communication strategies and public communications
  ●   Documenting and promoting IOM’s work
  ●   Informing IOM’s donors, partners, the media, the general public and others about IOM’s programmes and activities

In order to achieve these additional purposes,IOM may use or reproduce your data (always anonymized) in publications, promotional material, brochures, reports, articles, presentations, future exhibitions and display on the websites of IOM and other third-party electronic format media outlets.

5. Security of Your Data

IOM commits to make its best efforts to maintain the security and confidentiality of your personal information, including through encryption and other methods. As an international organization, IOM enjoys privileges and immunities that help protect your data from being accessed by governments and other third parties.

6. Confidentiality of Personal Data

Any personal data collected, received, used, transferred, or stored by IOM are protected by strict conditions of confidentiality and security, as detailed in the IOM Data Protection Principles. Aside from the limited situation described in point 7 below, IOM will not disclose your information to any third party without your prior informed consent. Access to your personal data will be limited only to IOM staff members on specific teams dedicated to managing MigApp. These staff members are strictly bound by confidentiality obligations.

7. Sharing Data to Prevent Harm, Report on Missing Migrants or Comply with International Law

IOM may preserve your information and share it with third parties if the Organization has a good faith belief that doing so is necessary to prevent death or immediate bodily harm to you or others, help locate migrants who have been reported missing, or prevent violations of international law.

8. Right to Change and Delete Your Data

You have the right to update all personal data you have supplied to MigApp, always remembering that the information you provide on MigApp must be true, accurate and up-to-date.

  ●   You may change your personal data in your account settings
  ●   If you choose to delete your MigApp account, all personal data will be deleted from IOM’s files and IOM will only keep aggregated data for statistical purposes

If your profile is inactive for two years, IOM will assume that you are no longer interested in the MigApp services and will delete your personal data from its files, only keeping aggregated data (always anonymized) for statistical purposes.

9. Requesting Personal Data

At any time, you may request a copy of all your personal data that has been gathered through MigApp regarding your account, which will then be sent to you via email. If you have not provided an email address with your registration, IOM will request one to send you your information. Please direct all requests for MigApp personal data to:
E-mail: migapp@iom.int.

10. Notification of Changes

IOM reserves the right to change this Privacy Policy at any time. Whenever changes are made, you will be notified and will need to agree in order to continue using the application.


General Terms and Conditions

1. Use of MigApp

You agree to the following obligations:

  ●   Not to use MigApp if you are under the age of 16
  ●   Not to misrepresent your relationship to another user
  ●   Not to use MigApp to act in an unlawful, obscene, discriminatory or abusive manner or promote such actions
  ●   Not to sell, rent, trade or otherwise monetize any feature of MigApp or any information accessed through the application
  ●   Not to collect, use, copy, or transfer any information obtained from MigApp without the consent of IOM
  ●   Not to use MigApp to violate the intellectual property rights of other persons or entities
  ●   Not to use bots, scripts or any other automated method to access and collect information on MigApp
  ●   Not to override any security feature of the application

2. Denying Access

IOM reserves the right to deny, at its sole discretion, any user access to the application or any portion thereof without notice.

3. Disclaimer

The content in MigApp is provided on an "as is" basis, without warranty of any kind. IOM specifically does not make any warranties as to the appropriateness, quality, timeliness, accuracy or completeness of the information and services offered through MigApp. While IOM cannot guarantee that there are no errors in the information provided, it does endeavour to correct errors that are drawn to its attention.

Established in 1951, IOM is the leading inter-governmental organization in the field of migration and works closely with governmental, intergovernmental and non-governmental partners.

With 166 member states, a further 8 states holding observer status and offices in over 100 countries, IOM is dedicated to promoting humane and orderly migration for the benefit of all. It does so by providing services and advice to governments and migrants.

IOM works to help ensure the orderly and humane management of migration, to promote international cooperation on migration issues, to assist in the search for practical solutions to migration problems and to provide humanitarian assistance to migrants in need, including refugees and internally displaced people.

The IOM Constitution recognizes the link between migration and economic, social and cultural development, as well as to the right of freedom of movement.

IOM works in the four broad areas of migration management:

  • Migration and development
  • Facilitating migration
  • Regulating migration
  • Forced migration

IOM activities that cut across these areas include the promotion of international migration law, policy debate and guidance, protection of migrants' rights, migration health and the gender dimension of migration.
